body:
Yes that make sense. But I don't think suggested code will pass tests as it solves the WEB form case but not REST inputs or a model class overriding `formName()` to return empty string. Maybe like this instead:

```php
protected function getValue($event)
{
    if ($this->value === null) {
        $request = Yii::$app->getRequest();
        $lock = $this->getLockAttribute();
        $formName = $this->owner->formName();
        $formValue = $formName ? ArrayHelper::getValue($request->getBodyParams(), $formName.'.'.$lock) : null;
        $input = $request->getBodyParam($lock, $formValue);
        $isValid = $input && (new NumberValidator())->validate($input);
        return $isValid ? $input : 0;
    }

    return parent::getValue($event);
}
```
@tarranjones do you want to send a PR or should I do it?

Also the getValue method doesn't take into consideration the `$owner->{$lock}` value, so the following code would throw a `StaleObjectException`

```php   
$user = User::findByUsername($username);
$user->last_logged_in = time();
$user->save();
```
This could be a possible fix. (added to @tunecino 's fix)
```php   
protected function getValue($event)
{
    if ($this->value === null) {
        $request = Yii::$app->getRequest();
        $lock = $this->getLockAttribute();
        $formName = $this->owner->formName();
        $formValue = $formName ? ArrayHelper::getValue($request->getBodyParams(), $formName.'.'.$lock) : null;
        $input = $request->getBodyParam($lock, $formValue);

        // additional code
        if($input === null && $this->owner->$lock){
           $input = $this->owner->$lock;
        }
        // 
        $isValid = $input && (new NumberValidator())->validate($input);
        return $isValid ? $input : 0;
    }

    return parent::getValue($event);
}
```

That wont work @tarranjones because if user doesn't submit the `version` number the script will load the value as stored in database which will bring back issue #9133.

The point of this behavior is to ensure **data is only updated/deleted if user submits a version number**. For the other tasks unrelated to handling user inputs, this behavior should not be attached. In such cases, I'd suggest extending the model class or create a different one to use internally. A parent class that only overrides `optimisticLock()` should safely throw `StaleObjectException` if the model gets updated by others on that bit of time between loading it from DB and saving it back.

Also, for any other different/custom cases, developers can always override that function on setup:
```php
public function behaviors()
{
    return [
        OptimisticLockBehavior::className(),
        'value' => function ($event) {
            // do your logic here and return some value
        },
    ];
}
```

@tunecino , yep that will definitely break it. 

I think i'll do something like this when/if the issue occurs. 

```php
public function behaviors()
{
    return [
        OptimisticLockBehavior::className(),
        'value' => function ($event) {
            $lock = $this->getLockAttribute();
            if( $lock && $this->owner->scenario === 'login'){
                return $this->owner->$lock; 
            }
            $this->value = null;
            return $this->getValue($event)
        },
    ];
}
```

Thanks
